<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-209-670  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 209 670.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Engineering Times  Feb 26 1990 n579 p14(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Commerce posing super challenge. (US Commerce Dept wants lessrestrictions on supercomputer trade limits than do the State andDefense departments)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Robinson, Brian.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The US Commerce Dept will challenge a proposed definition ofsupercomputers supported by the State and Defense departments.andO;The latter agencies want to modify the 1988 Omnibus Trade Act todefine supercomputers as any system with 100Mflop peak performanceor above.andP;  Such systems would incur strict licensing and exportlimits, ostensibly to prevent strategic technology from beingtransferred to communist countries.andP;  Commerce and its computerindustry supporters believe the proposed definition andcomplementary limits would tremendously increase the numbers ofcomputers classified as supercomputers, as computer technologyadvances are pushing workstations and personal computers into the100Mflop-plus performance range.andP;  Other computer producingcountries are not expected to impose similar limits.andO;Consequently, the definition could lose the US computer industryup to $10 billion in sales.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     ProposalInternational TradeGovernment AgencySupercomputersLimitationsPerformanceImpact AnalysisUnited States. Department of Commerce.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>